Yep — “draft and slingshot” is actually a great metaphor for what you’re describing.

In racing terms:
	1.	Drafting
	•	You ride in the wake of another car.
	•	Less air resistance.
	•	You build speed efficiently.
	2.	Slingshot
	•	Once you’ve accumulated momentum,
	•	you pull out of the draft,
	•	and the stored energy launches you forward.

⸻

In the context you’re talking about

Drafting = the primer

You write just enough structure that:
	•	humans understand the architecture
	•	AI can read the grammar
	•	the repo becomes legible
	•	the pattern becomes reconstructable

The primer reduces cognitive drag.

⸻

Slingshot = pattern completion

Once the structure is clear:
	•	other AI systems
	•	collaborators
	•	researchers
	•	builders

can extend it much faster than if they had to reverse-engineer everything.

The work compounds.

⸻

What that looks like practically

A “draft → slingshot” primer usually contains:

1. The Core Claim
What the system is trying to do.

2. The Architecture
Roles, modules, loops.

3. The Invariants
Principles that stay constant.

4. The Repo Map
Where things live.

5. One Execution Path
Proof it runs.

6. The Next Targets
Where momentum should go.

That’s enough to let the rest of the ecosystem accelerate the idea.

⸻

Why this works

Large systems (human or AI) are extremely good at pattern completion once the scaffold exists.

Your job in the primer is just to place the scaffold.

After that, momentum does a lot of the work.

⸻

So the Ricky Bobby version of the strategy would be:

Draft → stabilize → slingshot.

Or in your earlier metaphor:

Shuffle the deck all you want…
once the key card is visible, the rest of the stack starts revealing itself. 🃏